IRL, the effects of radiation exposure depend greatly on dosage. Humans can actually withstand a fairly large exposure without significant effects showing up right away. The damage is more long-term, usually in the form of hair loss and cancer. But even that takes a pretty high dosage to pose a significant threat. So if we see obvious signs of radiation, we would be wise to leave immediately, in which case the effects should be negligible.

But if you want there to be some kind of effect that would sort of make sense, maybe we could roll for the following symptoms:

1 - No effect
2 - Nausea
3 - Vomiting
4 - First degree burns (like a sunburn) plus 20% chance of cancer within d12 days
5 - Second degree burns (blisters and peeling) plus 40% chance of cancer within d8 days
6 - Third degree burns, immediately passes out, plus 60% chance of cancer within d6 days

The roll would be d4 + number of minutes spent there. (Counted as expedition response posts - 1.)

Instead of rolling for how many people are affected, just do the effects roll for each person.

Does that sound reasonable?

I'm sorry, GK, I don't want you to leave. But I think EoN is right. Let's talk through what all the objectives are, from the central conflict down to all the side-quests. And let's try to set up a GM process that is as clear as possible. Once we're all on the same page, I'm fine with you being in a GM role, as long as you stick to the plan you guys agree on.

GMs need to decide what the focus is going to be at any given point in the story. I think it might be okay to have two simultaneous crises, at most. Anything more than that is just too hard to manage. We should keep in mind that crises often come from the players themselves, thanks to craziness and injuries. So really, there's only room for one GM crisis at a time. It's fine if the crisis takes different forms at different times, but I think it would be best to try to keep the focus on the Mush, with other enemy encounters being somewhat less common.

I think it's actually pretty cool to have 3 different enemy factions fighting against each other, but IMHO, it would be best to avoid doing full combat mechanics between them. Since the GMs control all the enemies, just decide and describe the fights and outcomes, without rolling for any of it.

And we still haven't resolved a reasonable system of combat mechanics. At the end of the last thread, we discussed an idea that we should all declare our modifiers before we roll for them, so that other players could suggest changes to make them more reasonable. But we haven't been doing that, because it would really slow us down. So I'd like to propose some changes to combat mechanics that will keep it simple and reasonable:

ONLY ONE MODIFIER PER ROLL
Major Disadvantage -30%
Moderate Disadvantage -20%
Minor Disadvantage -10%
Equal Combatants (no modifier)
Minor Advantage +10%
Moderate Advantage +20%
Major Advantage +30%

Characters would be considered "Equal Combatants" if they are the same skill level. No need for any modifiers on either side.

Being one skill level above would be a Minor Advantage. Expert versus Skilled, or Competent versus Basic. That's a 10% chance of critical success.

Two skill levels above is a Moderate Advantage, 20% chance of critical success.

A difference of three or more skill levels would be a Major Advantage. An Expert fighter against a character totally Unskilled in combat would get +30% for each combat roll. That's a 30% chance of critical success, which is extremely powerful. Anything more than that just seems unreasonable, no matter how amazing the character is supposed to be.

Any other situational adjustments significant enough to affect the roll should be factored in to the advantage/disadvantage in a reasonable way. Examples would include injuries or the element of surprise. But there are too many possibilities to try to pre-define these things. Just try to keep it reasonable, and come up with a SINGLE modifier, rounded to the nearest TEN, maximum +30%, minimum -30%.

This is only a proposal. If anyone can think of any improvements, feel free to suggest them.
